** The figure above describes the graph.\nThe following figure shows all the possible MSTs:","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1489-find-critical-and-pseudo-critical-edges-in-minimum-spanning-tree/1489-msts.png","sequence":3,"sha256":"72e94792464d7fd945736d58812e32c58c25e9ced555d949483f6cb2f15b2614","type":"image"},{"sequence":4,"text":"Notice that the two edges 0 and 1 appear in all MSTs, therefore they are critical edges, so we return them in the first list of the output.\nThe edges 2, 3, 4, and 5 are only part of some MSTs, therefore they are considered pseudo-critical edges. We add them to the second list of the output.\n\n**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1489-find-critical-and-pseudo-critical-edges-in-minimum-spanning-tree/1489-ex2.png","sequence":5,"sha256":"43812b1b68694e0a872bc7581cdd46505a3885f135112e78d7666dec10a86e63","type":"image"},{"sequence":6,"text":"Input: n = 4, edges = [[0,1,1],[1,2,1],[2,3,1],[0,3,1]]\nOutput: [[],[0,1,2,3]]\nExplanation: We can observe that since all 4 edges have equal weight, choosing any 3 edges from the given 4 will yield an MST. Therefore all 4 edges are pseudo-critical.","type":"code"},{"sequence":7,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= n <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= edges.length <= min(200, n * (n - 1) / 2)`\n\n- `edges[i].length == 3`\n\n- `0 <= ai < bi < n`\n\n- `1 <= weighti <= 1000`\n\n- All pairs `(ai, bi)` are **distinct**.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Union-Find","Graph Theory","Sorting","Minimum Spanning Tree","Strongly Connected Component"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Hard","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given a weighted undirected connected graph with `n` vertices numbered from `0` to `n - 1`, and an array `edges` where `edges[i] = [ai, bi, weighti]` represents a bidirectional and weighted edge between nodes `ai` and `bi`. A minimum spanning tree (MST) is a subset of the graph's edges that connects all vertices without cycles and with the minimum possible total edge weight.\n\nFind *all the critical and pseudo-critical edges in the given graph's minimum spanning tree (MST)*. An MST edge whose deletion from the graph would cause the MST weight to increase is called a *critical edge*. On the other hand, a pseudo-critical edge is that which can appear in some MSTs but not all.\n\nNote that you can return the indices of the edges in any order.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1489-find-critical-and-pseudo-critical-edges-in-minimum-spanning-tree/1489-ex1.png]]\n\n**Input:** n = 5, edges = [[0,1,1],[1,2,1],[2,3,2],[0,3,2],[0,4,3],[3,4,3],[1,4,6]]\n**Output:** [[0,1],[2,3,4,5]]\n**Explanation:** The figure above describes the graph.\nThe following figure shows all the possible MSTs:\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1489-find-critical-and-pseudo-critical-edges-in-minimum-spanning-tree/1489-msts.png]]\n\nNotice that the two edges 0 and 1 appear in all MSTs, therefore they are critical edges, so we return them in the first list of the output.\nThe edges 2, 3, 4, and 5 are only part of some MSTs, therefore they are considered pseudo-critical edges. We add them to the second list of the output.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1489-find-critical-and-pseudo-critical-edges-in-minimum-spanning-tree/1489-ex2.png]]\n\nInput: n = 4, edges = [[0,1,1],[1,2,1],[2,3,1],[0,3,1]]\nOutput: [[],[0,1,2,3]]\nExplanation: We can observe that since all 4 edges have equal weight, choosing any 3 edges from the given 4 will yield an MST. Therefore all 4 edges are pseudo-critical.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= n <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= edges.length <= min(200, n * (n - 1) / 2)`\n\n- `edges[i].length == 3`\n\n- `0 <= ai < bi < n`\n\n- `1 <= weighti <= 1000`\n\n- All pairs `(ai, bi)` are **distinct**.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/find-cri